{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Grid · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Grid</h1>
    <p class="lead">Twelve-column flex grid, responsive containers, gutters, offsets.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <p>The grid pairs a <code>.row</code> with twelve <code>.col</code> children inside a <code>.container</code>. Each column is a flex child, and the column number controls its share of the row. Every utility carries a per-breakpoint variant so the same layout can re-flow at <code>sm</code>, <code>md</code>, <code>lg</code>, <code>xl</code>, <code>xxl</code>. See <a href="/breakpoints">Breakpoints</a> for the named widths.</p>
    <p>The whole grid is authored with logical properties. Containers center via <code>margin-inline: auto</code>, columns pad via <code>padding-inline</code>, and offsets use <code>margin-inline-start</code>. <code>dir="rtl"</code> flips the whole layout automatically.</p>
    <p>The grid uses flat, Bootstrap-style class names. <code>.col-md-6</code>, <code>.container-fluid</code>, <code>.offset-md-2</code>, <code>.row-cols-3</code>, <code>.g-md-3</code>. BEM stays inside the component files; the grid and the <a href="/utilities">utilities</a> follow this flat convention so the shape matches what consumers already know. See the <a href="/specification">spec</a> for where the line falls.</p>
    <p>Two conventions to flag up front. The <code>xs</code> tier has no infix, so the bare <code>.col-6</code> is the <code>xs</code> form (there&rsquo;s no <code>.col-xs-6</code>). And the grid is flex-only; Stisla doesn&rsquo;t ship an opt-in CSS Grid layer. Reach for CSS Grid directly on a component when you need explicit row tracks.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Containers</h2>
    <p>Three container variants: a responsive clamp, a full-width fluid, and per-breakpoint clamps that stay 100% wide until the named breakpoint and then pin to a max-width.</p>

    <h3>Responsive container</h3>
    <p><code>.container</code> grows in steps. Below <code>sm</code> it fills the viewport; from <code>sm</code> upward it pins to a max-width per breakpoint.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="container container-demo">.container</div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Fluid container</h3>
    <p><code>.container-fluid</code> stays 100% wide at every breakpoint. Use it inside an <code>.app-shell__main</code> when the content owns its own column rules.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="container-fluid container-demo">.container-fluid</div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Per-breakpoint containers</h3>
    <p><code>.container-{bp}</code> stays 100% wide below the named breakpoint and pins to its max-width at and above it. Useful when content should read full-bleed on phones and clamped on tablets.</p>
    {% call ui.code() %}
    <div class="container-sm">100% &lt; 640px, max-width 600px ≥ 640px</div>
    <div class="container-md">100% &lt; 768px, max-width 720px ≥ 768px</div>
    <div class="container-lg">100% &lt; 1024px, max-width 960px ≥ 1024px</div>
    <div class="container-xl">100% &lt; 1280px, max-width 1200px ≥ 1280px</div>
    <div class="container-xxl">100% &lt; 1536px, max-width 1440px ≥ 1536px</div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Max-widths</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Class</th>
          <th>xs (&lt;576)</th>
          <th>sm (≥576)</th>
          <th>md (≥768)</th>
          <th>lg (≥992)</th>
          <th>xl (≥1200)</th>
          <th>xxl (≥1400)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>.container</code></td><td>100%</td><td>540px</td><td>720px</td><td>960px</td><td>1140px</td><td>1320px</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.container-fluid</code></td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.container-sm</code></td><td>100%</td><td>540px</td><td>720px</td><td>960px</td><td>1140px</td><td>1320px</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.container-md</code></td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>720px</td><td>960px</td><td>1140px</td><td>1320px</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.container-lg</code></td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>960px</td><td>1140px</td><td>1320px</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.container-xl</code></td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>1140px</td><td>1320px</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.container-xxl</code></td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>100%</td><td>1320px</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Twelve columns</h2>
    <p>A <code>.row</code> divides into twelve. <code>.col-{n}</code> takes <code>n</code> of those at every breakpoint; <code>.col-{bp}-{n}</code> takes <code>n</code> from the named breakpoint upward.</p>

    <h3>Equal-width columns</h3>
    <p>Bare <code>.col</code> children split a row evenly.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo">
      <div class="col">.col</div>
      <div class="col">.col</div>
      <div class="col">.col</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Explicit widths</h3>
    <p>Mix <code>.col-{n}</code> classes for explicit widths. Children that overflow twelve wrap onto a new row.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo gy-2">
      <div class="col-6">.col-6</div>
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-8">.col-8</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Responsive widths</h3>
    <p>Stack on phones, two-up on tablets, three-up on desktops. Each breakpoint&rsquo;s class inherits from the one below, so write only the breakpoints that change.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo gy-2">
      <div class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4">.col-12 .col-md-6 .col-lg-4</div>
      <div class="col-12 col-md-6 col-lg-4">.col-12 .col-md-6 .col-lg-4</div>
      <div class="col-12 col-md-12 col-lg-4">.col-12 .col-md-12 .col-lg-4</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Auto-sizing</h3>
    <p><code>.col-auto</code> takes only the width its content demands. Other <code>.col</code> children split the remainder.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo">
      <div class="col-auto">.col-auto</div>
      <div class="col">.col (fills)</div>
      <div class="col-auto">.col-auto, a longer label</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Column alignment</h2>
    <p>The row is a flex container, so the <a href="/utilities">flex utilities</a> apply directly. Use <code>.align-items-*</code> on the row to align all columns on the cross axis (vertical, in a row-direction flex). Use <code>.align-self-*</code> on a single column to override.</p>

    <h3>Vertical alignment</h3>
    <p><code>.align-items-center</code> on the row centers every column. <code>.align-self-end</code> on one column overrides for that child.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row align-items-center grid-demo" style="min-height: 8rem;">
      <div class="col">.col</div>
      <div class="col">.col<br>two lines</div>
      <div class="col align-self-end">.col .align-self-end</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Horizontal alignment</h3>
    <p>When columns don&rsquo;t fill the row, <code>.justify-content-*</code> on the row controls how the free space distributes. The values are <code>start</code>, <code>end</code>, <code>center</code>, <code>between</code>, <code>around</code>, and <code>evenly</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row justify-content-between grid-demo">
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Per-breakpoint variants work the same way, e.g. <code>.align-items-md-center</code> or <code>.justify-content-lg-end</code>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Column breaks</h2>
    <p>Force a wrap inside a row with a full-width spacer. <code>&lt;div class="w-100"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</code> between two columns pushes everything after it onto a new line. Add display utilities to make the break itself responsive.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo gy-2">
      <div class="col-6 col-sm-3">.col-6 .col-sm-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-sm-3">.col-6 .col-sm-3</div>
      <div class="w-100"></div>
      <div class="col-6 col-sm-3">.col-6 .col-sm-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-sm-3">.col-6 .col-sm-3</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Make the break conditional with <code>&lt;div class="w-100 d-none d-md-block"&gt;</code>, which only forces the wrap at <code>md</code> and up.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Row columns</h2>
    <p><code>.row-cols-{n}</code> on the row sets every child to <code>1/n</code> of the row, no <code>.col-*</code> classes needed. Useful when the children are uniform (a card grid, a list of stats).</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row row-cols-2 row-cols-md-4 grid-demo gy-2">
      <div class="col">Item</div>
      <div class="col">Item</div>
      <div class="col">Item</div>
      <div class="col">Item</div>
      <div class="col">Item</div>
      <div class="col">Item</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Ranges from <code>1</code> to <code>6</code> by default. <code>auto</code> sizes each child to its own content width.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Reordering</h2>
    <p><code>.order-{n}</code> changes the visual order of flex children without touching the DOM. Useful when the natural reading order on mobile differs from the desktop layout, like a sidebar that lives after the article in markup but should sit to the left at <code>lg</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo">
      <div class="col order-3">First in DOM, last visually</div>
      <div class="col order-1">Second in DOM, first visually</div>
      <div class="col order-2">Third in DOM, middle visually</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p><code>.order-first</code> (<code>-1</code>) and <code>.order-last</code> (<code>6</code>) shortcut the extremes, and numeric values go <code>0</code> through <code>5</code>. Every step has a per-breakpoint variant like <code>.order-md-1</code> or <code>.order-lg-first</code>.</p>
    <p>These are flex <a href="/utilities">utilities</a> that the grid borrows. Column reordering is just the most common place you&rsquo;ll reach for them.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Offsets</h2>
    <p><code>.offset-{n}</code> pushes a column right (left in RTL) by <code>n/12</code> of the row. Use it for asymmetric layouts when a column starts past the row&rsquo;s leading edge.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo">
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4 offset-4">.col-4 .offset-4</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Per-breakpoint offsets follow the same pattern as columns. <code>.offset-md-3</code>, <code>.offset-lg-2</code>. Offset is implemented via <code>margin-inline-start</code> so RTL flips it cleanly.</p>
    <p>For asymmetric spacing without a fixed offset, reach for the margin utilities. <code>.ms-auto</code> on a column pushes it (and everything after it) to the row&rsquo;s trailing edge, the flex-aware version of <code>margin-left: auto</code>.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Nesting</h2>
    <p>A <code>.row</code> placed inside a <code>.col</code> resets the twelve-column scale within that column. The nested row uses its own gutters; the parent column&rsquo;s padding stays put.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo">
      <div class="col-9">
        Level 1: .col-9
        <div class="row grid-demo gy-2 mt-2">
          <div class="col-8">Level 2: .col-8 of the nested row</div>
          <div class="col-4">Level 2: .col-4</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-3">Level 1: .col-3</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Nesting deeper than two levels usually means the layout wants a real component instead of nested grids.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Gutters</h2>
    <p>Gutters are the horizontal and vertical space between columns. Default is <code>1.5rem</code> horizontal, zero vertical. Six ramp steps cover both axes, only horizontal (<code>gx-*</code>), or only vertical (<code>gy-*</code>).</p>

    <h3>No gutters</h3>
    <p><code>.g-0</code> flushes columns against each other. There is no <code>.no-gutters</code> class; the gutter ramp covers it.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row g-0 grid-demo">
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Custom horizontal gutter</h3>
    <p><code>.gx-{0&hellip;5}</code> sets only the horizontal axis. Vertical stays at the default.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row gx-5 grid-demo">
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Vertical gutters on a wrapped row</h3>
    <p><code>.gy-{0&hellip;5}</code> adds vertical space between rows when columns wrap.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row gy-4 grid-demo">
      <div class="col-6 col-md-3">.col-6 .col-md-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-md-3">.col-6 .col-md-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-md-3">.col-6 .col-md-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-md-3">.col-6 .col-md-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-md-3">.col-6 .col-md-3</div>
      <div class="col-6 col-md-3">.col-6 .col-md-3</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}

    <h3>Gutter ramp</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Class</th>
          <th>Value</th>
          <th>Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>.g-0</code> / <code>.gx-0</code> / <code>.gy-0</code></td><td>0</td><td>No gutter</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.g-1</code></td><td>0.25rem</td><td>Hairline grid</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.g-2</code></td><td>0.5rem</td><td>Tight grid</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.g-3</code></td><td>1rem</td><td>Comfortable grid</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.g-4</code></td><td>1.5rem</td><td>Default, same as the bare <code>.row</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.g-5</code></td><td>3rem</td><td>Wide grid</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Per-breakpoint variants apply per axis. <code>.gx-md-0</code> drops horizontal gutters at <code>md</code> and up while leaving vertical untouched.</p>

    <h3>Overflow at large gutters</h3>
    <p>Gutters are implemented as negative inline margin on <code>.row</code> and positive inline padding on each <code>.col</code>. A wide gutter like <code>.gx-5</code> (3rem) inside a tightly-padded container can push the row past the container&rsquo;s edge horizontally. Either cap the row with <code>.overflow-hidden</code>, or wrap it in a container with extra inline padding.</p>

    <h3>Edge-to-edge rows</h3>
    <p>To butt columns against the viewport edges, drop the container, zero the gutter, and cancel the row&rsquo;s default negative margin with <code>.mx-0</code>.</p>
    {% call ui.code() %}
    <div class="row g-0 mx-0">
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>RTL</h2>
    <p>The grid, containers, and offsets are authored with logical properties. Setting <code>dir="rtl"</code> on any ancestor flips column order, gutter sides, and offset direction with no extra stylesheet.</p>
    <p>The first column lands on the right in RTL, and the offset pushes the second column inward from the right edge instead of from the left.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div dir="rtl">
      <div class="row grid-demo gy-2">
        <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
        <div class="col-4 offset-4">.col-4 .offset-4</div>
        <div class="col-6">.col-6</div>
        <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
        <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Compare with the same grid in LTR.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div class="row grid-demo gy-2">
      <div class="col-4">.col-4</div>
      <div class="col-4 offset-4">.col-4 .offset-4</div>
      <div class="col-6">.col-6</div>
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
      <div class="col-3">.col-3</div>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Same markup, opposite reading direction. The flip costs nothing because every directional property in the grid uses its logical counterpart. <code>margin-inline-start</code> for offsets, <code>padding-inline</code> for column gutters, <code>margin-inline: auto</code> for container centering.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>Two CSS variables and a handful of Sass values drive every grid behaviour. The CSS vars retune live at runtime; the Sass values are compile-time and live in <code>foundation/_grid.scss</code> + <code>foundation/_containers.scss</code>.</p>

    <h3>CSS variables</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Variable</th>
          <th>Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--st-grid-gutter-x</code></td>
          <td>Horizontal gutter on <code>.row</code> + <code>.container</code> padding. Override on a row or globally.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>--st-grid-gutter-y</code></td>
          <td>Vertical gutter on <code>.row</code> between wrapped rows.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Sass variables</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Variable</th>
          <th>Default</th>
          <th>Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$grid-columns</code></td>
          <td>12</td>
          <td>Total column count. Drop to 8, 10, 16 for a different cadence; every <code>.col-{n}</code> regenerates against the new total.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$grid-row-columns</code></td>
          <td>6</td>
          <td>Maximum n for <code>.row-cols-{n}</code> utilities.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$grid-gutter-width</code></td>
          <td>1.5rem</td>
          <td>Default value seeded into <code>--st-grid-gutter-x</code> at the row mixin.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$gutters</code></td>
          <td>0, 0.25, 0.5, 1, 1.5, 3 (rem)</td>
          <td>Steps in the <code>.g-*</code> / <code>.gx-*</code> / <code>.gy-*</code> utility ramp.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$container-max-widths</code></td>
          <td>sm 540, md 720, lg 960, xl 1140, xxl 1320 (px)</td>
          <td>Max-widths for <code>.container</code> and per-breakpoint container classes.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>$breakpoints</code></td>
          <td>See <a href="/breakpoints">Breakpoints</a></td>
          <td>Named viewport widths. Change here, the grid + every utility re-emits.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
